For each of the following questions, outline how you could use an A/B test to find an answer. 
Be sure to identify all five key components of an A/B test.

1. Does a new supplement help people sleep better?

Two version - the original supplement and the new supplement
A sample divided into two groups - stock shelves with identical bottles but different ingredients listed.
A hypothesis - the new supplement will help people sleep better
Outcome - more bottles of that supplement will sell as they are more effective at providing the desired outcomes
Other measured variables - the same bottle design, same shelf placement, same checkout experience.

2. Will new uniforms help a gym's business?

Two versions - the original gym unifrom and the new gym uniform
A sample divided into two groups - gyms randomly selected throughout the city
A hypothesis - new gym uniforms will increase gym memberships
Outcome - new memberships.
Other measured variables - relative starting gym memberships, time of year, gym hours, gym popularity

3. Will a new homepage improve my online exotic pet rental business?

Two versions - Original homepage, new homepage
A sample divided into two groups - randomly selected website visitors
A hypothesis - A new homepage will increase exotic pet rentals
Outcome - Increased exotic pet rentals
Other measured variables - duration of new exotic pet rentals, time of day the website was visited, major events

4. If I put 'please read' in the email subject will more people read my emails?

Two versions - email without 'please read' subject line, email with 'please read' subject line
A sample divided into two groups - randomly sent emails to subscribed people
A hypothesis - Emails assigned a 'please read' subject line will be read more
Outcome - emails opened with a please read subject line
Other measured variables - devices open on, time emails were opened, day of the week emails were opened
